Private Set Intersection (PSI) enables two or more mutually distrustful parties to jointly compute the intersection of their sets, while revealing nothing beyond that intersection. Recently, a line of multiparty PSI has been explored in a malicious adversary model, i.e., any participant may deviate from the protocol. However, most of the works require a designated leader party to compute the intersection first by interacting with other parties, which brings heavy communication overhead for the leader. In addition, how to distribute the intersection fairly while preventing selective disclosure or premature aborts remains a challenging issue. In this paper, we propose a novel server-aided fair multiparty PSI protocol from lightweight cryptographic primitives, including oblivious key-value stores (OKVS) and oblivious pseudorandom functions (OPRFs). More concretely, our construction offloads heavy communication and computation tasks to the cloud server, which significantly alleviates the leader party’s workload. Moreover, the cloud sends a blinded intersection to all participants simultaneously, ensuring fair intersection recovery for all parties. Experimental results demonstrate that our protocol achieves overall performance comparable to the state-of-the-art (Nevo et al., CCS’21), while reducing the leader’s communication overhead by 2.61–29.67 ×.